parameters.description: Composite favorability threshold (0-1) above which recruitment pulse mechanism activates
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Minimum multiplicative favorability index (temperature × immigration × settlement × food) required to trigger episodic mass recruitment events characteristic of COTS outbreaks

parameters.description: Log coral cover at which settlement substrate (CCA) availability is half-maximal (untransformed: ~50%)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log coral cover where crustose coralline algae (CCA) availability for COTS larval settlement is reduced by 50% due to coral overgrowth. At low coral cover, CCA is abundant and settlement is high. At high coral cover, coral overgrows CCA and settlement declines. This creates an inverse relationship between coral cover and settlement substrate availability.

parameters.description: Steepness of settlement decline with increasing coral cover
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Rate at which settlement substrate availability declines as coral cover increases and overgrows crustose coralline algae. Higher values create steeper decline. Typical range 0.01-0.15 per percent coral cover.

parameters.description: Log critical coral cover below which food becomes limiting for COTS recruitment (untransformed: ~10%)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log minimum total coral cover required to support COTS juvenile survival and growth. Below this threshold, food limitation reduces recruitment success. Juvenile COTS are dietary generalists (biofilm, detritus, small coral) so threshold is low (5-15%). Only at very low coral does food become limiting enough to prevent outbreak persistence.

parameters.description: Steepness of food limitation response below threshold
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Rate at which food availability declines below the critical coral threshold. Higher values create sharper transition from adequate to limiting food. Controls how quickly recruitment collapses when coral becomes critically depleted.
